'Knowing what the future held was critically important.' 

During the time these shrines were active, a written form of language had not yet emerged in this part of Armenia so there are no written records of its local rulers.  

The diviner, Professor Smith continued, would have been a kind of an early risk analyst, assessing strategies and advising on politics and finances.  

'We call them 'shrines' because of two distinctive qualities of the spaces: they were quite intimate in scale, with not much room for public spectacle,' Professor Smith explained. 

'Yet they appear to have been religiously charged places, designed and built to host esoteric rituals with consecrated objects - secretive rites focused on managing risks by diagnosing present conditions and prognosticating futures.'

